dictable realm of the Pakistani urban bureaucracy, showing how the material forms of postcolonial bureaucratic documentation produce a distinctive political economy of paper that shapes how the city is constructed, regulated, and inhabited. Files, maps, petitions, and visiting cards constitute the enduring material infrastructure of more ephemeral classifications, laws, and institutional organizations. Matthew S. Hull develops a fresh approach to state governance as a material practice, explaining why writing practices designed during the colonial era to isolate the government from society have become a means of participation in it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBureaucracy -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aBureaucracyzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aBureaucracyzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCapitals (Cities) -- Pakistan -- Planning. 0aCapitals (Cities)zPakistanxPlanning. 0aCity planning -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aGovernment paperwork -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aGovernment paperworkzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aGovernment paperworkzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aIslamabad (Pakistan) -- Politics and government. 0aMunicipal government -- Pakistan -- Records and correspondence. 0aMunicipal governmentzPakistanvRecords and correspondence. 0aMunicipal governmentzPakistanxRecords and correspondence. 0aPublic records -- Pakistan -- Islamabad. 0aPublic recordszPakistanzIslāmābād. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aArbor, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095188440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951884423